<HL>
   No, It's Not a Mistake, and Yes,
   You Do Have to Pay for Tickets
   ----
   By Jacqueline Mitchell
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   CTA
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- Weary travelers may need coffee, an aspirin or
just some quiet time to themselves when they board an
airplane. But do they really want a bank economist's lecture
or a stand-up comic's routine?
   Like it or not, this live entertainment is just what
they'll get on Continental Express flights between Detroit
and Cleveland for one week beginning Aug. 6. During the
"Express Yourself" program, business writers and economists
will lecture in the morning, while comedians will perform on
the afternoon flights.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Both will have to be brief: The flying time between
Detroit City Airport and Cleveland Hopkins Airport is 17
minutes on the 30-passenger commuter planes.
   One featured speaker will be David L. Littmann, senior
economist and a first vice president of Manufacturers
National Bank of Detroit, a unit of Manufacturers National
Corp. "Economic Revelation While at Peak Elevation," is the
title of his 10-minute talk. It "will be a tale of two
cities, if you will," says Mr. Littmann, a discussion of the
local economies of Cleveland and Detroit. Mr. Littmann says
he has made many presentations before, but never while
airborne. Deadpan, he says: "My career must be taking off."
   The business experts won't be paid for their services,
says Continental Express, but the comedians will receive a
yet-to-be-determined fee. Comedy auditions will be held in
Detroit on Monday and in Cleveland on Tuesday.
   Business-travel experts aren't sure just what to make of
all this. "I've heard of news on a screen," says Linda
Marion, travel manager at GAF Corp. "But live entertainment
on the plane? I've never heard of that before."
   The Detroit-Cleveland flights cost $220 round-trip, while
restricted-fare tickets can be purchased for as low as $124.
Why not simply cut the price instead of resorting to
gimmickry? Continental Express, the commuter unit of
Continental Airlines Holdings Inc., says it wants to "build
awareness" of its service. If the idea catches on, a
spokeswoman says, it might be tried on the carrier's other
routes.
   Refunds won't be given if the lecture is boring or the
comedian is a dud. Mr. Littmann, however, says he plans to
offer a sort of flight insurance to passengers on his trip.
"I will provide cotton wads," he says, for passengers to use
as earplugs should they so choose.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900725-0102
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900725-0102.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Reuters Expects
   Slower Growth
   In Second Half
   ---
   Stock Falls 15% on Forecast
   Despite 23% Profit Gain
   For the First Six Months
   ----
   By Richard E. Rustin
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   RTRSY
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Reuters Holdings PLC said first-half pretax
earnings rose 23% from a year earlier, but Reuters stock
plummeted 15% as the news and financial information company
said it wouldn't match that performance in the second half.
   Reuters attributed its forecast to an increasingly high
rate of customer cancellations of its services and to the
adverse impact of the strong pound.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The forecast caused some analysts to lower their 1990
earnings estimates for the company, although they said they
still believed in its long-term growth potential.
   On London's stock exchange, Reuters fell #1.84 ($3.36) to
#10.45 ($19.09) a share on volume of 5.7 million shares. In
over-the-counter trading in the U.S., the company's American
depositary receipts plummeted $10 each, also a 15% drop, to
$56.25.
   The company said pretax profit was #167.1 million ($305.2
million), or 25.9 pence a share, compared with #135.9
million, or 20.6 pence a share. Sales grew 26% to #688.3
million from #548.3 million. Reuters declared a first-half
per-share dividend of 4.4 pence, up from 3.6 pence.
   "The recent stronger trend of sterling and high
cancellation rates will, if they persist, have a negative
impact," Glen Renfrew, chief executive officer, said. "On the
other hand, we have a large backlog of rental business to
install, and prospects remain good for outright sales of
trading-room systems. On balance, we expect continued good
growth but don't think growth rates for the full year will
match those of the first half."
   Company officials at a news conference declined to provide
figures on cancellations, but the company did report that the
number of customer teleprinter terminals declined to 4,161
from 4,956 during the first half. The number of video
terminals increased to 198,021 from 194,750.
   A strong pound makes British goods and services more
expensive and generally cuts demand by overseas customers.
   "Conditions in financial markets remain difficult, and
cancellations of Reuter services, which were already high,
have recently risen further, reflecting office and
departmental closures and economy drives by major clients,
including U.S. organizations with international networks,"
Mr. Renfrew said.
   He said cancellations were heaviest in Britain, the U.S.,
Taiwan, Hong Kong and Australia. "Gross new orders have held
up well, but the net after cancellations, while still
substantial, has fallen below last year's level," Mr. Renfrew
said.
   Brian Sturgess, an analyst at Barclays de Zoete Wedd
Securities Ltd., said he reduced his 1990 Reuters pretax
profit forecast to #324 million from #355 million because of
the currency and cancellation factors and because "staff has
increased as the company builds up to a bigger product base."
The company earned #283.1 million in 1989.
   Reuters said staff increased about 5% to 10,522 persons in
the first half, with most of the increase in the technical,
sales and marketing areas.
   Mr. Sturgess said the expected secondhalf slowdown in
Reuters's earnings growth is "just a pause" in an expected
pattern of long-term growth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
