yield 8.856% through Merrill Lynch Capital Markets. The
offering, through U.S. Auto Receivables Trust 1990-2, was
priced at a yield spread of 0.77 percentage point over the
Treasury's two-year note. Expected final maturity is July 15,
1993. Legal final maturity is Aug. 15, 1995. The securities
have a 1.57-year average life, assuming prepayments at 1% of
the original loan balance. A triple-A rating is expected from
S&amp;P and Moody's based on the quality of the underlying loans
and a subordinated class that now equals 9% of the senior
securities. The underlying loans are being serviced by
Chrysler Credit Corp., a unit of Chrysler Corp.
   Towers Healthcare Receivables Funding Corp. -- $56.5
million of two-year 1990 bonds backed by third party
health-care receivables at par to yield 10.20%. Towers
Healthcare Receivables Funding is a unit of Towers Financial
Corp., which underwrote the deal and is servicing the
underlying loans. The offering is rated double-A by Duff &amp;
Phelps Inc. Anthony DiNicolas, senior vice president,
finance, at Towers Financial said the "private placement
two-year note is the first time health-care receivables have
been used as exclusive collateral in a note transaction."
Funds paid to health-care facilities from insurance companies
after a person seeks health care are third party health-care
receivables.
                                                                                                       

