<HL>
   Mitel Files Claim
   Against AT&amp;T
   In Florida Court
   ----
   By Rose Tamburri
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   MLT T.MLT T BTY
</CO>
<IN>
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   OTTAWA -- Mitel Corp. said it filed a claim in a Florida
court against American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. for
allegedly spreading "misleading information" about the
company.
   The value of the claim wasn't disclosed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   John Jarvis, Mitel president, told a shareholders' meeting
here that AT&amp;T suggested in letters to Mitel's U.S. customers
that British Telecommunications PLC's plan to sell its 51%
interest in Mitel was "a cause for concern" about Mitel's
future. Mr. Jarvis said the AT&amp;T letters offered Mitel
customers a trade-in allowance if they exchanged Mitel's
telephone switching system for an AT&amp;T product.
   A spokesman for New York-based AT&amp;T said he had just
learned of the Mitel claim and couldn't comment on it until
it was examined.
   Mr. Jarvis said AT&amp;T's "aspersions" about Mitel's
"viability" were "without foundation." He said it was too
soon to assess what negative impact the "misleading
information" would have on Mitel. Mr. Jarvis said the company
was concerned that its "future business prospects and
reputation" could be damaged.
   Mr. Jarvis told shareholders that a "number of very
impressive companies" have expressed interest in buying
British Telecommunications' stake in Mitel. He said British
Telecommunications is talking to some of the companies.
   Mitel also reported yesterday that the company had a net
loss of 3.1 million Canadian dollars (US$2.7 million) on
revenue of C$100 million in the first quarter ended June 29.
In the year earlier, Mitel had net income of C$4.2 million on
revenue of C$102.7 million.
   Mitel shares closed at C$2.45 a share on the Toronto Stock
Exchange, down 15 Canadian cents.
   Mr. Jarvis said Mitel's first-quarter loss was in line
with the company's expectations. He said Mitel's forecasts
and advanced bookings had indicated a slow start in the year,
but he said there are some early indications that the Kanata,
Ontario, company has increased its market share in Britain in
the second quarter.
   "It is clear that these two facts taken together, slow
sales and market share increases, indicate the difficult
nature of the market and the appropriateness of our strategy
to become a more broadly based telecommunications company,"
he said.
   Mr. Jarvis said Mitel's sales outside North America were
down more than 8% in the first quarter from a year earlier.
Mr. Jarvis said he was confident that Mitel will have a
"positive performance" in these markets as the year develops.
   Mr. Jarvis said orders in markets outside North America
have been "quite strong" in recent weeks. He predicted the
company would have an upturn in sales in the second quarter.
   Mr. Jarvis also said Mitel plans to launch a major
advertising campaign in the fall "aimed at increasing
awareness of the company" in the U.S. and Britain. He said it
will help "counter the misleading information" distributed by
AT&amp;T.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900725-0077
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900725-0077.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Cap Cities/ABC
   Profit Edged Up
   In 2nd Quarter
   ----
   By Dennis Kneale
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   CCB
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Capital Cities/ABC Inc. posted a lackluster
1.5% rise in net income in the second quarter despite robust
results at the ABC network and warned that earnings in the
current quarter may fall below those of a year ago.
   The company's bleak forecast sent its common shares
tumbling by almost 9%. Capital Cities/ABC shares plunged
$55.50 to close at $533 in composite trading on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Capital Cities/ABC blamed the lukewarm second-quarter
results and the possible decline in third-quarter net on
sluggish ad sales at its television and radio stations and on
losses on the new baseball contract at its 80%-owned cable
channel, ESPN.
   Capital Cities/ABC posted second-quarter net of $142.3
million, or $8.19 a share, compared with $140.2 million, or
$7.83 a share, a year ago. Revenue rose 11% to $1.36 billion
from $1.23 billion.
   In last year's third quarter, the company earned $80.8
million or $4.56 a share; a decline in the current period
would mark the first year-to-year earnings drop for the
company since the first quarter of 1986.
   ESPN and the stations had been the company's two strongest
segments in recent years. Last year, ESPN earned well over
$100 million in pretax operating profit, and the eight
company-owned TV stations boast the highest profit margins in
the business. But in the second quarter, profits dropped
sharply at ESPN and other cable operations as the baseball
contract produced a $20 million loss. At the TV stations,
meanwhile, profits were up only modestly, and radio-station
profits fell below year-ago levels.
   Those two areas now look troubled just as Capital
Cities/ABC seems to have managed a turnaround at the two
major trouble spots of the past year or so: the ABC network
and some parts of the magazine-publishing business.
   ABC, now No. 2 and riding a turnaround in prime-time
ratings and well-ensconced in the No. 1 position in ratings
for the nightly news, posted a strong 15% rise in both sales
and earnings in the second quarter. The publishing business,
which makes up about 20% of total company revenue, had a 10%
rise in profits, the best performance for that segment in
more than a year. Those bright spots, however, weren't enough
to offset the other difficulties.
   Wall Street analysts had recently lowered their estimates
for the company, but the actual results came in below even
the revised expectations. David Londoner of Wertheim Schroder
&amp; Co. had expected $8.75 a share in net instead of the $8.19
the company turned in for the second quarter. For the third
quarter, he had first projected $5.80 a share in earnings,
then had lowered it to $5.30 a share vs. the year-earlier
period's $4.56 a share. "Now it looks as though it will be
$4.10 or $4.20," he said.
   Capital Cities/ABC executives are known for their cautious
outlook and for trying to avoid surprising Wall Street with
unexpected earnings problems. "They like to tell you the bad
news in advance, which I think everybody appreciates," said
Mr. Londoner. "Except on a day like this. They really took
things apart."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
