<HL>
   Morgan Stanley
   Stock Plunges
   On Profit News
   ---
   Firm Posts Decline of 48%
   In 2nd-Quarter Earnings;
   Salomon's Net Falls 53%
   ----
   By Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   MS SB PIPR ABSB
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Morgan Stanley Group Inc. stock was hammered
as the big securities firm posted a 48% drop in
second-quarter earnings, its weakest quarter in nearly two
years.
   Salomon Inc. reported second-quarter profit that was
halved from record yearearlier results. Two regional brokers
posted mixed results.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Morgan Stanley, dragged down by a 27% drop in investment
banking revenue, reported net income of $58 million, or $1.44
a share, down from $112.1 million, or $2.83 a share, a year
earlier. The year-earlier results were bolstered by a
one-time merchant banking gain.
   With some analysts expecting Morgan Stanley to earn as
much as $2 a share, the firm's stock was pummeled, falling
$6, or 8.3%, to $66.50 in heavy New York Stock Exchange
trading. The drop highlights how Wall Street recently has
punished companies -- even its own -- for earnings
disappointments, analysts said.
   "It's a sign of the times," said James Hanbury, an analyst
at Wertheim Schroder &amp; Co. Wall Street was thrown, he said,
because until now, Morgan Stanley "had always delivered the
goods."
   Revenue at Morgan Stanley fell 5% in the second quarter to
$1.45 billion from $1.52 billion. Trading revenue -- a big
earnings driver in the first quarter -- fell 11% to $201.6
million from $226.5 million. Asset management revenue and
stock commissions rose modestly.
   In a statement, Morgan Stanley officials said operating
performance "was affected by the continuing decline in
overall volume of investment banking business" and attributed
the trading drop largely to "decreased volatility in the
foreign exchange market." Much of the firm's first-quarter
trading gains stemmed from international stock markets.
   The last time Morgan Stanley earned less was 1988's third
quarter, when its net was $52.5 million.
   For the six months, Morgan Stanley earned $140.2 million,
or $3.51 a share, down from $193.3 million, or $4.86 a share,
a year earlier. Six-month revenue rose 3.2% to $2.84 billion
from $2.75 billion.
   Salomon earned twice as much as Morgan Stanley in the
second quarter, although it fell far short of its record
earnings in the 1989 second quarter. Salomon's net in the
most recent quarter slumped 53% to $120 million, or 89 cents
a share, from $253 million, or $1.89 a share. Revenue fell
10% to $2.1 billion from $2.33 billion.
   Earnings at Salomon's securities unit, Salomon Brothers
Inc., were bolstered by trading gains and an improvement in
investment banking revenue, particularly from stock
underwriting and advisory fees from a handful of merger
deals. The securities unit earned $211 million before taxes
in the quarter, compared with record pretax profit of $364
million a year earlier.
   Salomon Inc.'s Phibro Energy unit rebounded a bit,
reflecting stronger refinery margins. Phibro earned $49
million before taxes in the second quarter, a 47% drop from
$92 million a year earlier but far above $4 million in this
year's first quarter.
   Salomon's Philipp Brothers commodity unit continued to
perform poorly; analysts say the unit soon will be sharply
cut back. Philipp reported a $62 million pretax loss for the
second quarter, far wider than the $3 million pretax loss a
year earlier. Salomon said "adverse trading results" in
agricultural commodities hammered the unit's performance. In
past quarters, the villain was nonferrous metals trading.
   As a result, Salomon has told analysts it will drastically
cut back its commodity inventory and will restructure the
unit, resulting in significant layoffs. "If it doesn't
completely disband, lots of heads will be rolling," said one
analyst who was briefed by the firm. Salomon declined to
comment.
   For the six months, Salomon reported net of $239 million,
up 6% from $225 million in the year-earlier period. Revenue
jumped 15% to $4.45 billion from $3.87 billion. Salomon
shares closed unchanged at $24.50 in Big Board composite
trading.
   Two smaller regional firms posted mixed results.
   Alex. Brown Inc., Baltimore, reported a 6.7% increase in
second-quarter net to $4.5 million, or 29 cents a share, from
$4.3 million, or 26 cents a share. Earnings at Piper Jaffray
Inc., Minneapolis, fell 8.6% in the second quarter to $3.1
million, or 74 cents a share, from $3.35 million, or 83 cents
a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900725-0050
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900725-0050.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Bookshelf:
   Expats, Leftists, Skateboard Symbolism
   ----
   By Bruce Bawer
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<LP>
   Paul Micou is American, but the antecedents of his very
entertaining first novel, "The Music Programme" (Birch Lane,
240 pages, $16.95), are exclusively English. If his
understated satiric manner recalls the Evelyn Waugh of
"Decline and Fall" and "Black Mischief," and if his dramatis
personae remind one of the academics in David Lodge's novels,
his tale of privileged white folks stationed in a Third World
backwater -- where they drink too much, work too little and
live and love with exceptional superficiality -- brings to
mind Noel Coward's witty (though little read) novel "Pomp and
Circumstance."
   The "programme" of Mr. Micou's title is an international
organization headquartered at a wilderness compound in the
sweltering, strife-ridden African nation of Timbali. Its
putative mission is to unite the world through music, but its
real purpose is to perpetuate its own existence -- and, of
course, the high-paying jobs of its mostly indolent
employees. Among these are Dan O'Connor, a randy young
speechwriter, and Dr. Humphrey Lord, a Bach devotee who's at
work on a book proving that his hero was an atheist. ("He
found the going really rather tough," Mr. Micou writes, "but
he was dogged.")
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Then there's Ludvik Kastostis, the egomaniacal Czech
composer-in-residence who dismisses Mozart and Beethoven as
"nincompoops" and writes "music with an agenda" -- loud,
painfully dissonant avant-garde symphonies that call for
amateur pianists and animal noises.
   Kastostis and his colleagues lead a cushy life until a
determined young U.S. congressional aide, Charles "Crack"
McCray, comes to Timbali seeking evidence that the program's
American subsidy is being wasted. The evidence presents
itself immediately -- at Timbali's airport bar, in fact,
where a bibulous program employee, unaware of McCray's
mission, brags that he never goes into the office yet gets
promoted frequently anyhow.
   Mr. Micou, who has worked in Africa for a U.N. agency,
writes with an unfailing comic sense about the hypocrisies of
cultural bureaucracy and about the inconveniences and
corruptions of Third World life. He has a smart, brisk style
and does a first-rate job of introducing the characters and
milieu, so one is a bit disappointed by the way the plot
works itself out: One expects it to be cleverer, more neatly
orchestrated. Yet the book often is hilarious, and never less
than engaging.
   ---
   The same can't be said for Bob Katz's debut novel, "Hot
Air" (Birch Lane, 220 pages, $17.95). Danny Frank, the
"mildly progressive" proprietor of an ailing Washington,
D.C., speakers' bureau, tries to resuscitate the firm by
acquiring as a client a popular Latin American revolutionary
leader named Zapatu and taking him on a lecture tour of
American colleges.
   It's a promising satiric premise. But Mr. Katz makes only
mild, halfhearted stabs at satirizing Danny's
"progressivism," Zapatu's Marxism and the American academy's
fondness for south-of-the-border radicals. The fact is, Mr.
Katz finds all these things admirable; when Danny holds up
Zapatu as a moral exemplar and rants about "the religion of
capitalism" Mr. Katz apparently agrees with him.
   Where, then, is the humor in "Hot Air"? Well, Mr. Katz
tries to amuse us by disguising dreary leftist cliches about
the U.S. and capitalism as jokes. He doesn't do this very
successfully, since he's the sort who thinks the mere mention
of Gerald Ford's name is good for a laugh. Yet there are some
chuckles here, as when a Zapatu follower offers a bad-movie
eulogy of his leader: "When it is time for action, Zapatu is
the lion. When it is time for planning, Zapatu is the owl."
   ---
   Lewis Shiner's third novel, "Slam" (Doubleday, 233 pages,
$18.95), may be the first book to employ skateboarding as its
dominant symbol. Set in Texas, it's the story of Dave, who
has "never lived anywhere where people's cars started on the
first try." He's bitter about the six-month jail term he's
just served for tax evasion, but things seem to be looking
up: He's landed a job as caretaker of a recently deceased old
woman's manse and of the 23 cats to which she left her
fortune.
   Yet his orderly new life is soon disrupted by a host of
wackos, among them a sex-happy fundamentalist, an unruly
former cellmate and a local "UFO pastor." Dave soon realizes
that the house is just another prison and that the closest
he's come to real freedom is seeing a young skateboarder
momentarily suspended in midair. (The word "slam" is both a
synonym for jail and the term for what happens when
skateboarders wipe out.)
   Mr. Shiner means to do more than tell a story. Among much
else, he wants to illuminate the nature of individual
responsibility and the relation between the laws (civil,
social and natural) that we live by and the soul's need for
transcendence.
   "Slam," alas, is too slight a vehicle for so heavy a
thematic cargo. Yet Mr. Shiner's prose is very fine -- fast,
sharp, vivid, unsentimental -- and "Slam" has its funny and
touching moments.
   ---
   Mr. Bawer is a literary critic living in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900725-0049
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900725-0049.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Foreign Exchange:
   Dollar Is Mixed as Profit-Taking Helps
   Stabilize U.S. Currency; Pound Declines
   ----
   By Charles Tenny
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP JAPAN CANDA FREST
</CO>
<IN>
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Profit-taking helped the dollar stabilize
yesterday after the slide it suffered on a 56.44-point drop
in the Dow Jones Industrial Average the preceding day.
   As the industrial average rebounded to post a 17.82 point
gain, the U.S. currency finished mixed. Dollar trading was
eclipsed by activity in the pound, which dropped unexpectedly
against all major currencies, especially the mark.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Late in the New York trading day, the dollar was quoted at
1.6215 marks, down slightly from 1.6220 marks late Monday in
New York. The U.S. currency was also changing hands at 148.78
yen, up from 148.20 yen in New York late Monday. Sterling was
trading at $1.8133, down from $1.8255 late Monday.
   In Tokyo Wednesday, the dollar was trading at 148.95 yen
soon after the opening; it closed at 148.70 yen in Tokyo
Tuesday. Meanwhile, the U.S. currency was trading at about
1.6258 marks, up from Tokyo's Tuesday close of 1.6260 marks.
   The pound's fall, which began shortly after noon in New
York, only minutes after the end of the trading day in
London, dominated traders' attention on a suddenly busy
afternoon.
   "The primary activity has been in cross-rate trading,"
said Richard Witten, vice president and foreign exchange
trader at Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. in New York. He said the
market in particular focused on the pound and mark.
   Dealers have watched the pound hover mostly between 2.96
marks and 2.99 marks for several weeks, believing that the
British government wants to drive the currency to the
three-mark level before entering it into the fixed exchange
rate mechanism of the European Monetary System.
   The pound fell decisively out of that range yesterday,
slipping well below 2.93 marks before finding support at
2.9275 marks. Late in the U.S. day, sterling had recovered
somewhat to 2.9403 marks.
   The suddenness of the pound's decline surprised traders
because no special news had reached the markets after
sterling's close in London at 2.9541 marks. It had finished
in New York Monday at 2.9610 marks.
   "Fundamentally, there are no real reasons why the pound
should fall," said David Jaques, senior corporate trader at
Barclays Bank in New York. But he and others noted that the
pound has been attractive only for the high U.K. interest
rates that the government has used against inflation.
Overall, the country is besieged by high inflation and
unemployment and by low productivity, he said.
   "A decline like this overall isn't something that should
be a surprise" in light of the economy's troubles, said Mr.
Jaques. "But the actual timing of this move didn't have any
explanation."
   Goldman's Mr. Witten noted that the pound's easing against
the mark actually began last week, as dealers were drawn
toward the German currency on fears of a drop in interest
rates in the U.S.
   Yesterday, when the pound began to slide in New York,
trading volume became "quite, quite heavy," noted Ty Tan, a
dealer with Deutsche Genossenschaftsbank in New York.
   The dollar ended European dealings weaker against major
currencies. One dealer said the Federal Reserve might be
tempted to lower interest rates in the wake of Monday's sharp
drop in the U.S. stock market.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current
delivery settled at $367.90 an ounce, down $1.20. Estimated
volume was a moderate four million ounces.
   In Hong Kong Wednesday, gold opened for trading at $366.45
an ounce.
</TEXT>
