<HL>
   Who's News:
   Arco Shifts Managers,
   Taps Environmentalist
   For Added Board Seat
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   ARC WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- Atlantic Richfield Co. made several
management changes and elected a new director of the oil, gas
and mineral concern.
   Named senior vice presidents were Harrell E. Bilhartz Jr.,
E. Kent Damon Jr., Anthony G. Fernandes and William C.
Rusnack.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Bilhartz, previously president of Arco Coal Co.,
became president of Arco Alaska Inc., succeeding William E.
Wade Jr., a senior vice president, who became president of
Arco Oil &amp; Gas Co. Mr. Wade succeeded James A. Middleton, who
became head of West Coast petroleum operations.
   Mr. Damon, previously vice president and investment
officer, became senior vice president, planning and control.
   Mr. Fernandes, previously vice president and controller,
succeeded Mr. Bilhartz as president of Arco Coal.
   Mr. Rusnack, previously vice president, corporate
planning, became president of Arco Transportation Co.,
succeeding Harold C. Heinze, who resigned to pursue other
interests, Arco said.
   Also, Steven J. Shapiro, assistant treasurer, was elected
vice president, corporate planning, succeeding Mr. Rusnack.
Marie L. Knowles, vice president, financial, control and
planning, at Arco International Oil &amp; Gas Co., succeeded Mr.
Fernandes as vice president and controller.
   Frank D. Boren was elected a director, increasing board
membership to 16. Mr. Boren is a lawyer, a real estate
developer and former president of the Nature Conservancy. He
is the first professional environmentalist named to the
board, Arco said.
</TEXT>
