<HL>
   Business Brief -- Consolidated Edison Co.:
   Utility's 2nd-Period Profit
   Fell 25% to $49.1 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   ED
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Consolidated Edison Co. reported second-quarter net income
sank 25%, reflecting higher operating expenses and interest
charges and lower earnings from investments.
   The New York-based utility's profit fell to $49.1 million,
or 18 cents a share, from $65.7 million, or 24 cents a share,
a year earlier. Revenue rose 3% to $1.26 billion from $1.22
billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Operating expense rose 4.4% to $1.16 billion, reflecting
particularly a 15% jump in the costs of fuel Con Ed uses and
of power it buys from outside sources. Investment earnings
dropped 38% to $15.6 million, while net interest charges rose
8.7% to $61.6 million.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Con Ed's shares closed unchanged at $23 a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900725-0033
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900725-0033.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Melville Corp.:
   Retailer's 2nd-Quarter Net
   Rose 27% on Higher Sales
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   MES
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
SPECIALTY RETAILERS (OTS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Specialty retailer Melville Corp., Rye, N.Y., reported
second-quarter earnings rose 27% on a 16% sales increase,
noting that the strong, Easter-week selling period occurred
in the quarter.
   Net income rose to $78.3 million, or 72 cents a share,
from $61.3 million, or 56 cents a share, a year earlier.
Sales rose to $1.95 billion from $1.68 billion. The 1989
Easter week was in the first quarter.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the first six months, earnings were flat at $86
million, or 76 cents a share, compared with $85.9 million, or
78 cents share, a year ago. The company cited softness in the
apparel and footwear businesses in New England and
larger-than-expected markdowns in leather apparel.
</TEXT>
