<HL>
   Deutsche Bank Unit Plans to Purchase
   Equity Stake in Gleacher's Mergers Firm
   ----
   By Michael R. Sesit and Randall Smith
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   G.DBK U.MGF
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Morgan Grenfell Group PLC, a unit of Deutsche
Bank AG of West Germany, plans to buy an equity stake in the
mergers advisory boutique of Eric Gleacher, former head of
mergers and acquisitions at Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   The new firm will be called Gleacher Morgan Grenfell Inc.,
and both Mr. Gleacher and the Deutsche Bank unit will share
expenses evenly, according to people familiar with the
transaction. Mr. Gleacher last night confirmed the equity
stake, but wouldn't give financial or other details.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   With the investment, C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc.,
the U.S. investment banking arm of London-based Morgan
Grenfell, will close its corporate finance and merger
departments here. Late yesterday, 36 people in those
departments were told they would be out of jobs in two weeks.
   People familiar with the transaction said that the
investment in Gleacher &amp; Co. was negotiated by Morgan
Grenfell's chief executive officer, Michael Dobson, and
chairman, John Craven, without the advance knowledge of top
executives at C.J. Lawrence here.
   The investment in Mr. Gleacher's firm is the latest in a
series of alliances between overseas securities firms and
U.S. merger advisory boutiques in the past few years.
   Nomura Securities Co. of Japan has purchased a 20% stake
in Wasserstein Perella &amp; Co. for $100 million, Nikko
Securities Co. of Japan paid the same amount for a 20%
interest in Blackstone Group, and Yamaichi Securities Co. of
Japan paid $101 million for a minority stake in Lodestar
Partners.
   A veteran of Lehman Brothers, Mr. Gleacher was head of
mergers and acquisitions throughout the late 1980s at Morgan
Stanley &amp; Co. He led the firm to a bonanza in high-profile
takeover advisory business during the heyday of corporate
raiders' hostile bids for blue-chip U.S. firms. But he left
the firm early this year to form the small boutique.
   Mr. Gleacher has since disavowed any interest in expanding
to a size that would rival the Wasserstein or Blackstone
firms. So far this year, his only major deal as an
independent has been to advise ConAgra Inc. on the $1.3
billion acquisition of Beatrice Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900725-0026
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900725-0026.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Ivaco Inc.:
   Canadian Steelmaker to Sell
   2 Units to BTR of Britain
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   IVA.A U.BTR
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
PULP, PAPER, PACKAGING (ALL TYPES) (PUL)
</IN>
<LP>
   Ivaco Inc., a Montreal-based steelmaker, said it agreed to
sell two wholly owned subsidiaries to a unit of BTR PLC, a
British holding company, in a transaction that would reduce
Ivaco's long-term debt by about 125 million Canadian dollars
(US$108.2 million).
   Ivaco declined to disclose terms of the transaction, but
reports from London said BTR agreed to pay US$112 million.
The two Ivaco subsidiaries operate plants in the U.S. and
Canada that make fabrics used in the paper-making industry.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The transaction, which requires approval by U.S. and
Canadian regulators, would result in a pretax gain of about
C$30 million, Ivaco said. Ivaco had 1989 profit of C$12.9
million, after a C$19.8 million one-time charge and a C$4.3
million loss on discontinued operations. On Dec. 31, it had
long-term debt of C$550.6 million.
</TEXT>
