<HL>
   Pepsi-Cola to Sell Franchise
   To Earvin `Magic' Johnson
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   PEP
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Pepsi-Cola Co. is selling its Washington, D.C., bottling
franchise to a partnership headed by basketball star Earvin
"Magic" Johnson and Black Enterprise magazine publisher Earl
Graves, individuals familiar with the transaction said.
   Mr. Johnson, of the Los Angeles Lakers, had told Pepsi of
his interest in owning such an operation when he signed a
multi-year endorsement contract with the soft drink firm last
year, according to industry executives. In recent years,
Pepsi has generally been acquiring bottling franchises from
independent owners, rather than selling them. Pepsi-Cola is a
unit of PepsiCo, Purchase, N.Y.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Washington franchise sells about four million cases a
year, according to Beverage Digest, a trade newsletter.
Individuals close to Pepsi said the Johnson/Graves
partnership is not acquiring a stake in the plant that
services their franchise area.
   "For Pepsi it isn't so much good will with minorities,"
said Paine Webber Inc. analyst Emanuel Goldman of Pepsi's
motivation for the deal. "It's having Magic Johnson, who
appeals to a wide segment of the population."
   Although Pepsi officials declined to comment, they are
expected to announce details of the transaction at a
Washington news conference today. Mr. Johnson's business
representatives could not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900725-0022
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900725-0022.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   McDonnell Unit Says
   Lloyd's of London
   Is Suing the Company
</HL>
<DATE>
07/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   MD
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   HUNTINGTON BEACH, Calif. -- McDonnell Douglas Space
Systems Co. said Lloyd's of London filed a $6 million suit
against the company for alleged negligence in the failed
launch of a satellite last year.
   The suit stems from an accident at Cape Canaveral, Fla.,
in June 1989, when a crane hook smashed into an $80 million
communications satellite on a Delta rocket. The satellite,
built by Ford Aerospace Corp. and insured by Lloyd's, was
repaired for around $10 million and launched later. Lloyd's
wants to recover part of the costs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The suit alleges that the McDonnell Douglas Corp. unit,
which was responsible for launching the satellite,
"negligently and carelessly planned, simulated, trained for
and conducted the handling and removal procedure," causing
the crane cable to break while loading the satellite onto the
rocket.
   The McDonnell Douglas unit said it has requested that the
suit, filed last month, be transferred to federal court in
Orlando, Fla., from Brevard County Circuit Court in Florida,
as the accident occurred on federal government property.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
